    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I was reading a section about how things can go wrong though, like how debris or even insects can cause issues. What are the most common ways a pitot tube gets blocked or fails during flight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Common causes of pitot tube failure or blockage during flight include ice formation, bird strikes, or debris ingestion. Bird strikes, particularly those involving medium-sized birds like pigeons or squirrels, are often reported causes of pitot tube icing, which can prevent the tube from breaking apart and causing airspeed indications to become unreliable. Additionally, insects, snow, and hail can also enter the pitot tube and cause blockages. These issues can lead to reduced or false airspeed readings, which can impact pilot decision-making and potentially result in loss of control.",
      "source": "target",
